{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650474","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650474"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:13:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:13:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18406"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.1,0.2,0.5,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11124"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11124"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"11269"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25788"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of Golgi tendon organs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monitor joint position","Facilitate muscle contraction","Initiate the inverse myotatic reflex","Detect changes in muscle length","Detect changes in temperature"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGolgi tendon organs are sensory receptors found at the junction between muscles and tendons. They play a crucial role in monitoring muscle tension and protecting muscles from excessive force. Golgi tendon organs primarily \u003Cstrong\u003Einitiate the inverse myotatic reflex\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a protective mechanism that prevents muscle damage by causing muscle relaxation in response to excessive tension. This reflex helps to maintain muscle integrity during activities that generate high levels of force.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetecting changes in muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E is the function of muscle spindles, not Golgi tendon organs. \u003Cstrong\u003EMonitoring joint position\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily performed by joint receptors, not Golgi tendon organs. \u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitating muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as Golgi tendon organs actually inhibit contraction to prevent damage. \u003Cstrong\u003EDetecting changes in temperature\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by thermoreceptors, not Golgi tendon organs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Golgi tendon organs are sensory receptors located at the junction of muscles and tendons.","They are responsible for detecting changes in muscle tension.","Golgi tendon organs initiate the inverse myotatic reflex, which helps prevent muscle damage from excessive force."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 55; pg. 690","Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96235"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:02:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:02:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11124"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ud